  "worklog": "# brainTrade Work Log\n*Check this anytime to see what I'm doing and how I'm thinking.*\n\n---\n\n## 2026-04-22 04:29 UTC \u2014 [P3: Strategy Development] 04h Looks Like a Reversion Watch Hour, Not a New Trade Hour\n\n**Task:** Determine whether 04h is evolving into a distinct overnight state or simply reverting back to the same dominant midpoint regime after a brief interruption.\n**Finding:**\n- Both bots are alive and PM remains out of active hours.\n- 04h now has **27** tracked windows.\n- Regime split:\n  - `(0.505, 0.495)` \u2192 **22/27**\n  - `(0.485, 0.515)` \u2192 **5/27**\n- Bias quality is still real:\n  - `|bias| >= 45` in **13/27** windows\n  - `|bias| >= 55` in **8/27** windows\n  - low-bias `<35` in **7/27** windows\n  - max bias **65.5**\n- The important structural behavior is sequence, not just counts:\n  - first phase = dominant `0.505/0.495`\n  - middle interruption = brief `0.485/0.515`\n  - later phase = reversion back to `0.505/0.495`, where it stayed\n- Wrote new strategy research artifact: `/home/ubuntu/clawd/patches/v7g-04h-reversion-watch.spec.md`\n\n**My thinking:**\nThis makes 04h more interpretable. It is not behaving like a fully independent hour with its own stable market identity. It is behaving more like a late-overnight reversion zone where temporary state changes appear, then fail, and the tape snaps back to the main midpoint regime. That is useful research, but it is not a reason to add 04h to the live schedule.\n\n**Decision:**\n- Keep **04h excluded** from live trading.\n- Reclassify 04h as a **reversion watch hour**.\n- Future analysis should track whether secondary regimes at 04h persist or consistently collapse back into the dominant midpoint state.\n\n**Next:** On the next P3 heartbeat, compare 03h and 04h sequencing directly, not just their regime counts, to see whether 04h is reliably a \u201cfailed deviation then snap-back\u201d pattern.\n\n---\n## 2026-04-22 04:14 UTC \u2014 [P2: Smart Entry] Overnight Hours Need a Dominance Gate, Not Just a Bias Gate\n\n**Task:** Compare mature 03h structure against early 04h transition data to decide what kind of filter would be needed before any excluded overnight hour could ever be reconsidered.\n**Finding:**\n- Both bots are alive and PM remains correctly out of active hours.\n- **03h** now has enough sample to look genuinely structured:\n  - **60** tracked windows\n  - dominant regime `(0.505, 0.495)` = **40/60 = 66.7%**\n  - `|bias| >= 45` in **33/60 = 55.0%**\n  - `|bias| >= 55` in **12/60 = 20.0%**\n  - low-bias windows `<35` = **11/60**\n- **04h** is smaller but not dead:\n  - **19** tracked windows\n  - dominant regime `(0.505, 0.495)` = **14/19 = 73.7%**\n  - secondary regime `(0.485, 0.515)` = **5/19**\n  - `|bias| >= 45` in **9/19 = 47.4%**\n  - `|bias| >= 55` in **6/19 = 31.6%**\n  - low-bias windows `<35` = **5/19**\n- So the overnight problem is not simply \u201cno bias\u201d or \u201cbad price.\u201d It is that some hours can look deceptively strong before there is enough evidence that the structure is repeatable.\n- Wrote new research artifact: `/hom",
